result.execSummary:
The defendant Arturo Cabrera Rangel was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Defendant granted a payment plan of $50.00 per month to 08/10/2015

records.addlTxt: Prosecutor Lyndsey A.B. Brunette and Defendant, Arturo Cabrera Rangel appeared, pro se.    Defendant finalized  waiver of  right to an attorney after full colloquy  Took time to think over offer, reconvened 2:26 pm, he decided to go on his own without an attorney
THE DEFENDANT ENTERED A PLEA OF NOT GUILTY

Pre-trial conference at 06-17-2015 10:00 am.
Status conference at 07-09-2015 11:30 am.

The defendant shall have no contact with C.H.B. or A.V. of any kind, whether direct or indirect, including in person, in writing, by phone, by e-mail or other electronic means, through a third party or in any other way.  Defendant shall not possess or consume any alcohol, and not go into places that sell alcohol except incidentally such as a grocery store, convenience store or gas station or other such place where alcohol is not sold for consumption on the premises.

District Attorney Lyndsey A Boon Brunette appeared on behalf of the State;  Defendant appeared in person, pro se,  via video conference from Clark County Jail  Defendant advised of right to an attorney    Interpreter Susan Rascon was sworn and present to interpret, telephonically.  Pre-trial conference scheduled for June 17, 2015 at 10:00 am.  Status conference scheduled for July 9, 2015 at 11:30 am.  THE DEFENDANT ENTERED A PLEA OF NOT GUILTY
